  "response": "**Receiver:** `d`\n\n**Function to fix first:** The formatter at line 41 in `src/date.ts` — it's the higher-risk site because it combines two crimes on the same line. `crime_00004` flags `d.getMonth()` at L41 disagreeing with `d.getUTCFullYear()` at L9; `crime_00026` shows L41 also uses `+ d.getUTCFullYear()` in a hand-rolled string concat. So `d` at L41 mixes UTC-year with local-month inside one constructed string — the exact silent-off-by-an-offset bug the detector exists to catch.\n\n**Refactor (pick UTC):**\n\nReasoning for picking UTC over local: the L9 site already uses `getUTCFullYear`, the file deals with stored/serialised dates (timezone-unsafe parses at L29/L33 flag the same), and the PRD's general guidance is \"UTC for storage, local only at the display boundary.\" Local is the minority here.\n\nConcrete change at L41:\n- Replace `d.getMonth()` → `d.getUTCMonth()` so the receiver speaks one family.\n- Then collapse the manual `\"…\" + d.getUTCFullYear() + …` concat into `d.toISOString().slice(0, 10)` (or `Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-CA', { timeZone: 'UTC', … }).format(d)` if you need a specific shape). That closes `crime_00026` in the same edit and removes the risk of dropped zero-padding or zero-indexed-month bugs that the manual concat invites.\n\nLeave L9 alone — it's already UTC and consistent after this change.\n\nWhat I'd **not** do in this pass: touch `getUTCMonth()` -vs- `getMonth()` elsewhere in the file blindly. The detector reports one receiver (`d`) with disagreement; other variables in `src/date.ts` may legitimately be display-side. Unify per-receiver, not per-file.",
